    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2696630028" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2696630028" />
    <a title="Vartika" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/63883678-vartika"><img alt="Vartika" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1635798462p2/63883678.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2696630028?book_show_action=true">Feb 02, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Vartika" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Vartika" href="/user/show/63883678-vartika">Vartika</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9789385436154" href="/book/show/28054831-the-good-person-of-szechwan">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2696630028" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13437647809694244865">[3.5 stars]<br/><br/>The Good Person of Szechuan is a parable play, which means that readers and audiences must expect morality as a central concern therein. However, given that the play is one of Brecht&apos;s, there is also an attempt to engage audiences cerebrally rather than emotionally. <br/><br/>Emotional and cerebral is also how one may choose to describe the prostitute Shen Tei — the eponymous good person, who is discovered by three gods in what seems like pre-Communist China, and provided money to start anew as</span>
  <span id="freeText13437647809694244865" style="display:none">[3.5 stars]<br /><br />The Good Person of Szechuan is a parable play, which means that readers and audiences must expect morality as a central concern therein. However, given that the play is one of Brecht's, there is also an attempt to engage audiences cerebrally rather than emotionally. <br /><br />Emotional and cerebral is also how one may choose to describe the prostitute Shen Tei — the eponymous good person, who is discovered by three gods in what seems like pre-Communist China, and provided money to start anew as a tobacconist — and Shui Ta, the former's 'cousin', respectively. In its ten acts, the play fascinates one by showing us how different two sides of the same crossdressing coin can be, and how sustenance in line with the moral commandments of the gods requires for a person to be split down the middle and engage in both kindness and shrewdness. A feminist reading of the play may also highlight how Shen Tei, a woman, is perfectly capable of exhibiting shrewd 'manliness' in the guise of Shui Ta, while also shedding light on the portrayal of the overpowering 'feminine' emotionality of Shen Tei vis-a-vis Yang Sun. It is this emotionality that perhaps helps Brecht achieve the distance that he aims for, along with punctuating the play with songs that mimic folk traditions. <br /><br />Poverty and exploitation can also be seen to be in dialogue with each other: Brecht highlights the exploitation of poverty and the exploitation by poverty in characters such as Yang Sun and the families that Shen Tei shelters or helps. After all, the play is the Gods' search for good person in the wretched modern world. That the play ends; unexpectedly for many; in the middle of unresolved action may defy expectations born of convention, but delivers a strong message regarding the central question of morality and of life itself. Moreover, the ineptitude of the Gods makes us question the need for and nature of such models. <br /><br />It would not be incorrect to say that this play is based on a host of confusions brought about by a meditation on the idea of 'the meek inheriting the earth' and leaves the readers or audiences at a juncture that does not answer the dilemmas highlighted by the play but rather encourages one to think for themselves. By not providing a conclusive end to the action in the play, Brecht breaks convention and engages the audience more than traditional theatre could perhaps afford to. <br /><br />The Good Person of Szechuan is enjoyable, often frustrating, and action-packed, and was quite nice to read without witnessing the action on stage as well.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13437647809694244865" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

