<div id="review_914529757" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/914529757" />
    <a title="Momina Masood" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17262906-momina-masood"><img alt="Momina Masood" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1423900868p2/17262906.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/914529757?book_show_action=true">Apr 19, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Momina Masood" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Momina Masood" href="/user/show/17262906-momina-masood">Momina Masood</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17262906-momina-masood?shelf=plays">plays</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17262906-momina-masood?shelf=german-lit">german-lit</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer914529757" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8739250071640418973">I have very mixed feelings about this play. Shen Te makes Jean Valjean look like a dream: can&apos;t you both be rich <i>and</i> good? Not all of the good suffer and not all of the evil ones prosper, or do they? And if all of us decide to become Shen Te, wouldn&apos;t all of us be happy? The dilemma arises when the good are outnumbered by the greedy and the selfish. Then, like in Setzuan, the exploitation of the virtuous begins which gives birth to the Shui Tas of society. Goodness stops being useful. <br/><br/>Another th</span>
  <span id="freeText8739250071640418973" style="display:none">I have very mixed feelings about this play. Shen Te makes Jean Valjean look like a dream: can't you both be rich <i>and</i> good? Not all of the good suffer and not all of the evil ones prosper, or do they? And if all of us decide to become Shen Te, wouldn't all of us be happy? The dilemma arises when the good are outnumbered by the greedy and the selfish. Then, like in Setzuan, the exploitation of the virtuous begins which gives birth to the Shui Tas of society. Goodness stops being useful. <br /><br />Another thing: <i>which</i> kind of goodness is more useful? The selfless, abundant charity of Shen Te or the evenhanded practicality of Shui Ta. The latter made honest workers of those who Shen Te simply spoiled. But the latter are also those who eventually morph into the bloodsucking bureaucrats that socialist literature harps about. A balance, then, between the two? My head hurts with all this thinking.<br /><br />I must start reading up on Marx as Brecht was a proud Marxist from what I've heard. A Marxist reading might prove helpful in understanding this play, I hope. But one thing that seems clear as daylight: Brecht was not a religious man and was highly sceptical of Christian theology (which isn't a big surprise, him being a Marxist and all). The unfairness of the world, the indifference of the gods: it's all there. Though the Epilogue sounds like an innocent plea from an innocent man who simply seeks answers, Brecht's views on religion are more than emphatic in this play.<br /><br />Anyways, this play is recommended to all those who like to think about the mysteries of life and why things are the way they are. One can at least accredit Brecht with presenting a part of our lives, an unfortunate aspect of reality, if not the complete truth. I am still much of a believer in human goodness and divine justice to accept that all the world is Setzuan incarnate. <br /><br />My first of Brecht. I am hoping it won't be the last.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8739250071640418973" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


